Talk #1 - Erik Hanchett - Getting Started With Amplify For Web Developers
items.description:
I'm a developer advocate for Amplify at AWS. I've worked as a software developer for many years at small startups, larger companies and everything in between. When I'm not teaching people, or creating tutorials, I love puzzles and spending time with my family.

AWS offers a lot of services. Cognito, S3, Hosting, and Lambda functions to name a few. What if we could access those services without having to learn devops, infrastructure as code, and intricate IAM rules? So as front-end developers we can focus on the front-end.

Amplify has us covered! In this talk I'll discuss how to get started with Amplify, how it can be used by Front-end and mobile developers to use AWS services and some of the nice features it has. This will include:

  • UI Components Library
  • Authentication connected components
  • Amplify Studio with our Figma to Code integration

items.summary: Talk #2 - Lucas Lu - Introduction to Communication between Software Systems
items.description: In the era of cloud computing and distributed micro-services, a critical question is how computers communicate with each other networks which contain machines running software on different operating systems and programs in different programming languages. This lecture will cover how complex data structures are packaged into formats that can be understood by different hardware and different programming langugages in compressible formats that work well with internet protocols. Then it will cover RPC (remote procedure calls) and API (application programming interfaces), the two primary frameworks of cross software communication, and which parts of the internet stack they interact with.Brief summary of topics1. Data Serialization: formats like XML, Protocol Buffers, JSON2. Communication Frameworks: APIs and RPC3. OSI layers used for APIs and RPC

items.summary: 1. Taking a deeper dive into the world of databases (Tom, Vani, Blu from Couchbase)
2. Compressing Decades into Weeks: How to Gain Years of Practical Real-World Experience the Fastest Way Possible (Edwin Sarmiento)
items.description:
Breaking into tech, whether you're a student completing a degree or a professional switching careers, can be a Catch-22. The dream jobs you want require years of experience.

But how do you get the job experience necessary if nobody wants to hire you because you don't have any experience?

The job search process can be a very frustrating when you know you can do the job but keep getting disqualified because you don't have the years of experience.

It's time to fix this.

This talk will show you how to gain years of practical, real-world experience the fastest way possible and help you land that dream job you've always wanted. Drawing from my personal experience of breaking into tech without a computer-related degree nor certifications, I'll share the hacks I learned the hard way to bypass the "years of experience" requirement in tech job postings.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Edwin M Sarmiento is the Managing Director of 15C, a consulting company that specializes in designing, implementing, and managing high-availability infrastructures. He is a former Microsoft Data Platform MVP of 12 years standing, a Microsoft Certified Master for SQL Server, and author of the book The SQL Server DBA's Guide to Docker Containers. He is very passionate about technology, and has interests in music, social psychology, professional and organizational development, leadership, and management matters when not working with databases.
